text.Taxonomy and naming:
The species was first formally described by Robert Chinnock in 2007 and the description was published in Eremophila and Allied Genera: A Monograph of the Plant Family Myoporaceae. The specific epithet (rostrata) is a Latin word meaning "curved" or "beaked" referring to the shape of the fruits.There are two subspecies

Eremophila rostrata  Chinnock subsp. rostrata which flowers from June to September and has leaves that are usually 20–40 mm (0.8–2 in) long with a single spine on the end and flowers that are usually 24–30 mm (0.9–1 in) long;
Eremophila rostrata subsp. trifida Chinnock which flowers from August to October and has leaves that are mostly 50–75 mm (2–3 in) long, with 3 spines near the end and flowers that are mostly 15–22 mm (0.6–0.9 in) long;
